06927nam a22007215i 9780773557857DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735578577 a10.1515/97807735578572doi  a(DE-B1597)657149  a(OCoLC)1090412919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBH301.P64b.A78 2019 7aPHI0260002bisacsh04a111.8522300aArt as Revolt :bThinking Politics through Immanent Aesthetics /ced. by David Fancy, Hans Skott-Myhre. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b14 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tTechnology and Futures -- tActualization of the Virtual through an Aesthetic Encounter with Virtual Reality Technology -- tPlaying with Fire: A Quasi-Causal Machine in Multiple (Mostly Russian) Februaries -- tCreepers, Pixels, and the Nether: Performing Minecraft Worlds -- tDecolonizing Science Fiction, Performing Postcolonial Lines of Flight -- tAesthetics and Resistance -- tThe Blues as Minoritarian Vernacular -- tRakuness: Schizoanalysis and the Work of Paul Soldner -- tMale Becomings: Queer Bodies as Aesthetic Forms in the Post-Pornographic Fanzine Butt -- tDeleuze and Guattari's Geophilosophy Meets 2Pac's Thug Life: Resistance to the Present -- tAuto-Ethnographies of the Post-Identitarian -- tThought beyond Brains: Performing Immanent Zombie Politics through Autoethnography -- tWhen Simulation Becomes Simulacrum: “Reversing Platonism” with Deleuze in Live Role Play -- tNeither Subject nor Object -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow can we imagine a future not driven by capitalist assumptions about humans and the wider world? How are a range of contemporary artistic and popular cultural practices already providing pathways to post-capitalist futures? Authors from a variety of disciplines answer these questions through writings on blues and hip hop, virtual reality, post-colonial science fiction, virtual gaming, riot grrrls and punk, raku pottery, post-pornography fanzines, zombie films, and role playing. The essays in Art as Revolt are clustered around themes such as technology and the future, aesthetics and resistance, and ethnographies of the self beyond traditional understandings of identity. Using philosophies of immanence – describing a system that gives rise to itself, independent of outside forces – drawn from a rich and evolving tradition that includes Spinoza, Nietzsche, Deleuze, and Braidotti, the authors and editors provide an engrossing range of analysis and speculation. Together the essays, written by experts in their fields, stage an important collective, transdisciplinary conversation about how best to talk about art and politics today. Sophisticated in its theoretical and philosophical premises, and engaging some of the most pressing questions in cultural studies and artistic practice today, Art as Revolt does not provide comfortable closure. Instead, it is understood by its authors to be a “Dionysian machine,” a generator of open-ended possibility and potential that challenges readers to affirm their own belief in the futures of this world. Contributors include Timothy J. Beck (University of West Georgia), Mark Bishop (Independent Scholar), Dave Collins (University of West Georgia), David Fancy (Brock University), Veronica Pacini-Ketchabaw (University of Western Ontario), Malisa Kurtz (Independent Scholar), Nicole Land (Ryerson University), Eric Lochhead (Youth Author Calgary Alberta), Douglas Ord (Doctoral Student University of Western Ontario), Joanna Perkins (Independent Scholar), Peter Rehberg (Institute for Cultural Inquiry—Berlin), Chris Richardson (Young Harris College), Hans Skott-Myhre (Kennesaw State University), and Kathleen Skott-Myhre (University of West Georgia).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAestheticsxPolitical aspects. 0aArtsxPolitical aspects. 0aPopular culture. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBeck, Timothy J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBishop, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Dave, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFancy, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFancy, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKurtz, Malisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLand, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLochhead, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrd, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPacini-Ketchabaw, Veronica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerkins, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRehberg, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkott-Myhre, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkott-Myhre, Hans, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSkott-Myhre, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773557857?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773557857423Coveruhttps